=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">environmentally problematic</a>, or by proof of stake, which <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26319066.271646/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cubHluYWxkZW4uY29tL3Byb29mLW9mLXN0YWtlLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBf45b91cb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">has its own problems</a>, but by me. I maintain the led=
ger in Microsoft Excel. Here is a copy of the ledger as of 9 a.m. today[2]:=
</p><!--[if mso]>
<table width=3D"550"><tr><td><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/im=
ages/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/i4loEwne3GSc/v1/-1x-1.png" width=3D"550" /></td></t=
r></table>
<div style=3D"display:none">
<![endif]--><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHB=
FdfxIU/i4loEwne3GSc/v1/-1x-1.png" style=3D"max-width: 550px; display: block=
; width: 100%; margin-top: 20px;" /><!--[if mso]>
</div>
<![endif]--><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you want to buy some of my quad=
rillion ExcelCoins, send me an email[3]; I will make a market at $0.99 bid =
/ $1.01 offered,[4] though of course that is subject to change with market =
conditions.[5]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course ExcelCoin started =
as a currency, a form of =E2=80=9Cdigital cash,=E2=80=9D but what is powerf=
ul about the concept is that in principle you could track any sort of asset=
 using the same underlying technology (me typing in Excel). For instance yo=
u could extend the ExcelCoin technology to track not merely fungible tokens=
 like coins, but also=C2=A0<em>non</em>-fungible tokens, where each entry i=
n the ledger represents a unique asset. For instance:</p><!--[if mso]>
<table width=3D"550"><tr><td><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/im=
ages/users/iIyChnKQ1lHc/i7dEpxHtdlXY/v1/-1x-1.png" width=3D"550" /></td></t=
r></table>
<div style=3D"display:none">
<![endif]--><img alt=3D"" src=3D"https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iIyChn=
KQ1lHc/i7dEpxHtdlXY/v1/-1x-1.png" style=3D"max-width: 550px; display: block=
; width: 100%; margin-top: 20px;" /><!--[if mso]>
</div>
<![endif]--><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is just a toy example =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0why would you want me to write =E2=80=9Ca picture of a cat=E2=80=
=9D next to your name on a list? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but with a little imaginati=
on you can see how powerful it could be. For instance, we could track real =
estate this way. I could write down=C2=A0a list of all the houses in my tow=
n and who owns them;=C2=A0to transfer ownership we could just update the en=
tries on my list. As of yet my list in Excel does not carry any=C2=A0<em>le=
gal=C2=A0</em>ownership rights; it does not sync up with, or supersede, the=
 legal property registry. But I think that you will agree that it is a much=
 more efficient and technologically advanced system than the old legal syst=
em of property registration on paper in dusty archives, so I think in the l=
ong run it is likely to win out.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is st=
upid, why is it stupid. The easy answer is that it is <em>technologically</=
em> stupid. Actual cryptocurrencies (and blockchain systems for NFTs, propo=
sed blockchains for=C2=A0real estate, etc.) have a <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26319066.271646/aHR0cHM6Ly9iaXRjb2luLm9yZy=
9iaXRjb2luLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8b206508" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">distributed con=
sensus mechanism</a> for updating their shared ledger, proof-of-stake or pr=
oof-of-work or some other mechanism that lets the participants in the syste=
m verify and collectively control the ledger. Whereas I can type whatever I=
 want in Excel. If you buy some ExcelCoins from me and I delete your entry =
in my Excel ledger, you don=E2=80=99t have any ExcelCoins anymore, and what=
 sort of system is that?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A better answer is=
 that it is=C2=A0<em>socially=C2=A0</em>stupid, because the person maintain=
ing the ExcelCoin ledger is me, and I am obviously kidding. You should not =
trust me to maintain the ExcelCoin ledger, because I invented ExcelCoin as =
a joke about ledgers. On the other hand millions and millions of people own=
 U.S. dollars, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/263=
19066.271646/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMT=
ktMDYtMTgvZmFjZWJvb2std2lsbC1tYWtlLXRoZS1tb25leS1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDExMDIyX=
01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rl=
cm09MjIwMTEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9ec29=
a33" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> which means precisely</a>=C2=A0that some bank has a list and =
there is an entry for them on that list. It=E2=80=99s probably not in Excel=
, but same basic idea: The bank has a list of dollars in its accounts, the =
list is not kept via any sort of consensus mechanism or blockchain or whate=
ver; the bank just keeps the list using, uh, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/26319066.271646/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2VhbHRoc2ltcGxl=
LmNvbS9lbi1jYS9tYWdhemluZS9jb2JvbC1jb250cm9scy15b3VyLW1vbmV5/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBa11d4f55" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">Cobol</a>. But you (mostly) trust the bank to=
 maintain the list, because among other things (1) it has a good track reco=
rd of maintaining the list, (2) it has good commercial incentives to mainta=
in the list, (3) it has powerful regulatory and legal incentives to maintai=
n the list, etc.[6] The bank=E2=80=99s list is not any great shakes technol=
ogically, and 100 years ago=C2=A0banks kept very similar lists using pen an=
d paper. This system of lists is=C2=A0not flawless =E2=80=94=C2=A0sometimes=
 the banks <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2631906=
6.271646/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3NpbnNpZGVyLmNvbS9zYW50YW5kZXItYmFuay1hY2=
NpZGVudGFsbHktcGF5cy1wZW9wbGUtMTc1LW1pbGxpb24tY2hyaXN0bWFzLWRheS0yMDIxLTEy/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd10482b0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">mess up the lists</a>! =E2=80=94=
 but it is not howlingly stupid either, in the way that ExcelCoin is. It's =
very normal and standard and millions of people rely on it without thinking=
 about it.[7] ExcelCoin is stupid not because I keep it <em>in Excel</em>; =
it's stupid because=C2=A0<em>I=C2=A0</em>keep it in Excel.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">On Friday=C2=A0Moxie Marlinspike <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26319066.271646/aHR0cHM6Ly9tb3hpZS5vcmcvMjAy=
Mi8wMS8wNy93ZWIzLWZpcnN0LWltcHJlc3Npb25zLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB33=
3c1c3a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">wrote a blog post</a> on =E2=80=9CMy first impressions of w=
eb3.=E2=80=9D Marlinspike is a famous cryptographer and computer-security g=
uy, the inventor of the Signal app, etc., and the post has gotten a ton of =
attention in the Web3 (and Web3-skeptical) world; it=E2=80=99s great and I =
recommend it highly and I will only scratch the surface of it here. One rel=
evant point=C2=A0is that distributed ledgers are not necessarily a complete=
=C2=A0<em>technological=C2=A0</em>solution for asset ownership:</p><blockqu=
ote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most people think of images and digital ar=
t when they think of NFTs, but NFTs generally do not store that data on-cha=
in. For most NFTs of most images, that would be much too expensive.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead of storing the data on-chain, NFTs instead=
 contain a URL that=C2=A0<em>points to</em>=C2=A0the data. What surprised m=
e about the standards was that there=E2=80=99s no hash commitment for the d=
ata located at the URL. Looking at many of the NFTs on popular marketplaces=
 being sold for tens, hundreds, or millions of dollars, that URL often just=
 points to some VPS running Apache somewhere. Anyone with access to that ma=
chine, anyone who buys that domain name in the future, or anyone who compro=
mises that machine can change the image, title, description, etc for the NF=
T to whatever they=E2=80=99d like at any time (regardless of whether or not=
 they =E2=80=9Cown=E2=80=9D the token). There=E2=80=99s nothing in the NFT =
spec that tells you what the image =E2=80=9Cshould=E2=80=9D be, or even all=
ows you to confirm whether something is the =E2=80=9Ccorrect=E2=80=9D image=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So as an experiment, I made an NFT that c=
hanges based on who is looking at it, since the web server that serves the =
image can choose to serve different images based on the IP or User Agent of=
 the requester. For example, it looked=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/26319066.271646/aHR0cHM6Ly9vcGVuc2VhLmlvL2Fzc2V0c=
y8weDVjNjFhZmE0NzU3MGFiMmI1NjI2MDZmYTU3ODIyMTMwNWIxMmMzMDcvMQ/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB325ad313" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">one way</a>=C2=A0on OpenSea,=C2=A0<=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26319066.271646/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9yYXJpYmxlLmNvbS90b2tlbi8weDVjNjFhZmE0NzU3MGFiMmI1NjI2MDZmYTU3ODIyMT=
MwNWIxMmMzMDc6MT90YWI9ZGV0YWlscw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7b3abc37" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">another way</a>=C2=A0on Rarible, but when you buy it and view =
it from your crypto wallet, it will always display as a large [poop] emoji.=
 What you bid on isn=E2=80=99t what you get. There=E2=80=99s nothing unusua=
l about this NFT, it=E2=80=99s how the NFT specifications are built. Many o=
f the highest priced NFTs could turn into [poop]=C2=A0emoji at any time; I =
just made it explicit.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The NFT=
 does not by itself convey ownership of the underlying thing in either a le=
gal or practical sense. It conveys ownership in some more metaphysical sens=
e: If you buy a Bored Ape Yacht Club NFT, then the people who are part of t=
he BAYC NFT community will treat you as the owner of your ape. This is esse=
ntially a social fact and can be true=C2=A0<em>even if the immutable code o=
f the blockchain says that you don=E2=80=99t own the ape</em>, because you =
were <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26319066.2716=
46/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudmljZS5jb20vZW4vYXJ0aWNsZS95M3YzbnkvYWxsLW15LWFwZXMtZ29u=
ZS1uZnQtdGhlZnQtdmljdGltcy1iZWctZm9yLWNlbnRyYWxpemVkLXNhdmlvcnM/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB64e71280" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">hacked or whatever</a>. The technology is a=
 scaffolding on which to hang a social system, but the social system is wha=
t does or does not convey =E2=80=9Cownership=E2=80=9D in a meaningful sense=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also the technology is totally centralize=
d? Marlinspike goes on:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After a=
 few days, without warning or explanation, the NFT I made was removed from =
OpenSea (an NFT marketplace). ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What I fo=
und most interesting, though, is that after OpenSea removed my NFT, it also=
 <strong>no longer appeared in any crypto wallet on my device</strong>. Thi=
s is web3, though, how is that possible?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A =
crypto wallet like MetaMask, Rainbow, etc is =E2=80=9Cnon-custodial=E2=80=
=9D (the keys are kept client side), but it has the same problem as my dApp=
s above: a wallet has to run on a mobile device or in your browser. Meanwhi=
le, ethereum and other blockchains have been designed with the idea that it=
=E2=80=99s a network of peers, but not designed such that it=E2=80=99s real=
ly possible for your mobile device or your browser to be one of those peers=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A wallet like MetaMask needs to do basic =
things like display your balance, your recent transactions, and your NFTs, =
as well as more complex things like constructing transactions, interacting =
with smart contracts, etc. In short, MetaMask needs to interact with the bl=
ockchain, but the blockchain has been built such that clients like MetaMask=
 can=E2=80=99t interact with it. So like my dApp, MetaMask accomplishes thi=
s by making API calls to three companies that have consolidated in this spa=
ce.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For instance, MetaMask =E2=80=A6=C2=A0d=
isplays your NFTs by making an API call to OpenSea. ...</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">All this means that if your NFT is removed from OpenSea, it al=
so disappears from your wallet. It doesn=E2=80=99t functionally matter that=
 my NFT is indelibly on the blockchain somewhere, because the wallet (and i=
ncreasingly everything else in the ecosystem) is just=C2=A0<em>using the Op=
enSea API to display NFTs</em>, which began returning 304 No Content for th=
e query of NFTs owned by my address!</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">The technology behind OpenSea is not quite =E2=80=9COpenSea keeps a =
list, in Excel, of who owns which NFTs.=E2=80=9D The underlying list is kep=
t on the blockchain; it=E2=80=99s just that OpenSea can modify its version =
of the list however it wants, and its modifications are in practice pretty =
binding. And in fact there are regular rounds of stories in which (1) some =
gullible crypto guy hands out his private key to anyone who asks for it, (2=
) his NFTs get stolen, (3) he complains on Twitter, (4) he gets a major NFT=
 marketplace to lock trading in his stolen NFTs, and (5) everyone writes ar=
ticles like =E2=80=9Cha ha ha you don=E2=80=99t like decentralization so mu=
ch now do you?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is fine,=
 though, Web3 proponents argue, because OpenSea=E2=80=99s ability to act ar=
bitrarily is limited by community standards. The open immutable blockchain =
still exists, so you=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>compare what OpenSea says to wh=
at the blockchain says. (Perhaps not=C2=A0<em>with MetaMask</em>, but the p=
ossibility exists.) If OpenSea=E2=80=99s list did not conform to what its c=
ustomers expected =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it arbitrarily ignored the blockchain, =
if it let people claim NFTs that weren=E2=80=99t theirs, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0then everyone would take their apes elsewhere. But this is pretty much w=
hy people trust banks too! The essential protections are social, not techno=
logical.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Marlinspike:</p><blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When you think about it, OpenSea would actually be m=
